{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"494b7c72-dfff-4bf2-ae6d-25ef0291054b","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** on the `MauiAppBuilder` to map platform events to cross-platform hooks.\n\nIn your `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnPause\n        })\n        .OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnStop\n        }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // runs on iOS DidEnterBackground\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` at the top.\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` compiler directives so each platform only compiles its own handlers.\n- The delegates receive the native platform object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), giving you full access to native APIs if needed.\n- Other events are available too — `OnResume`, `OnCreate`, `WillEnterForeground`, etc.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e86de854-f9ae-4f8a-986c-0c720d5dc55c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development. I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":370,"requestId":"D448:27C37:1D7DBCB:210E3E7:6A07C168"},"id":"336c46c2-9bca-4a30-b3f4-b72f8a2ab861","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:59:28.323Z","parentId":"dd08c104-2af8-4a75-a9d3-61b7e7daa823"}
